---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import BarChart from '../../../components/BarChart.astro';
import KeyFigure from '../../../components/KeyFigure.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Share of Immigrants by Country: 20-Nation Comparison — Official Data | Immigration Factbook"
  lang="en" altHref="/themes/demographics/"
  description="Systematic comparison of immigrant and foreign-born population shares across 20 Western nations, drawn from each country's official national statistics. Australia 32% to Italy 9.1%."
  type="Dataset">

<main class="theme-page">
  <div class="page-header">
    <nav class="breadcrumb">
      <a href="/en/">Immigration Factbook</a> <span>›</span> <span>Thematic Comparisons</span>
    </nav>
    <h1>Share of Immigrants in the Population — 20-Country Official Comparison</h1>
    <p class="intro">
      This page provides a systematic comparison of the share of immigrants or foreign-born residents in the total population across 20 Western and English-speaking nations, drawn directly from each country's official national statistics agency. Data sources include the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS), the Swiss Federal Statistical Office (FSO/OFS), Statistics Canada, and equivalent bodies in each country.
    </p>
    <p class="intro-sub">
      Important: Definitions vary significantly across countries ("foreign-born", "foreign nationals", "persons with a migration background", etc.). These figures are not directly comparable on a like-for-like basis. Definitions and sources are shown in the table below.
    </p>
    <div class="lang-switch">
      <a href="/themes/demographics/">🌐 日本語で読む</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="charts-section">
    <div class="key-figures-row">
      <KeyFigure
        value="32.0%"
        label="Highest: Australia (2025, foreign-born share of population)"
        tone="accent"
      />
      <KeyFigure
        value="9.1%"
        label="Lowest in this comparison: Italy (2024, foreign nationals share)"
        tone="primary"
      />
    </div>

    <BarChart
      title="Immigrant / Foreign-Born Population Share — 20 Countries, Latest Official Data"
      unit="%"
      bars={[
        { label: 'Australia', value: 32.0, note: 'Foreign-born (June 2025, ABS)' },
        { label: 'New Zealand', value: 28.8, note: 'Foreign-born (2023 Census, Stats NZ)' },
        { label: 'Switzerland', value: 27.7, note: 'Foreign nationals — permanent residents (Dec 2025, FSO)' },
        { label: 'Canada', value: 23.0, note: 'Immigrants (2021 Census, Statistics Canada)' },
        { label: 'Sweden', value: 21.0, note: 'Foreign-born (Dec 2024, Statistics Sweden)' },
        { label: 'Austria', value: 20.5, note: 'Foreign nationals (April 2026, Statistics Austria)' },
        { label: 'United Kingdom', value: 19.0, note: 'Foreign-born (June 2024 estimate, ONS)' },
        { label: 'Norway', value: 17.5, note: 'Immigrants (both parents foreign-born) (Jan 2026, SSB)' },
        { label: 'United States', value: 14.3, note: 'Foreign-born (2023 ACS, US Census Bureau)' },
        { label: 'Portugal', value: 14.0, note: 'Foreign nationals (Dec 2025, INE Portugal)' },
        { label: 'Spain', value: 13.96, note: 'Foreign nationals (Jan 2025, INE Spain)' },
        { label: 'Belgium', value: 13.8, note: 'Non-Belgian nationals (Jan 2026, Statbel)' },
        { label: 'Denmark', value: 12.6, note: 'Immigrants (excl. descendants 3.7%) (Jan 2025, Statistics Denmark)' },
        { label: 'Ireland', value: 12.0, note: 'Non-Irish nationals (2022 Census, CSO)' },
        { label: 'Finland', value: 11.7, note: 'Foreign-origin (1st & 2nd gen.) (Dec 2025, Statistics Finland)' },
        { label: 'France', value: 11.3, note: 'Foreign-born immigrants (2024 provisional, INSEE)' },
        { label: 'Czechia', value: 10.38, note: 'Foreign nationals (Dec 2025, Czech Statistical Office)' },
        { label: 'Italy', value: 9.1, note: 'Foreign nationals (Dec 2024, ISTAT)' },
        { label: 'Netherlands (ref.)', value: 13.5, note: 'Foreign-born (2023 estimate, CBS) — provisional after methodology change; not directly comparable' },
        { label: 'Germany (ref.)', value: 25.6, note: 'Migration background — Migrationshintergrund (2024, Destatis) — broader definition, not comparable to other countries' },
      ]}
      sourceLabel="National statistics agencies: ABS, Stats NZ, FSO, Statistics Canada, SCB, Statistics Austria, ONS, SSB, US Census Bureau, INE Portugal, INE Spain, Statbel, Statistics Denmark, CSO, Statistics Finland, INSEE, Czech Statistical Office, ISTAT, CBS, Destatis"
      sourceUrl="/"
      sourcePrefix="Sources: "
    />
    <p class="chart-note">
      Netherlands and Germany are shown as reference figures only (grey bars) — their definitions are not directly comparable to the other countries. Germany's 25.6% (Migrationshintergrund) includes anyone with at least one foreign-born parent, making it broader than foreign-born or foreign-national measures. The Netherlands figure (approx. 13.5%) is a provisional estimate following CBS's 2024 methodology change.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="methodology-note">
    <h2>Key Methodological Notes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Foreign-born vs. foreign nationals</strong>: "Foreign-born" (Australia, New Zealand, Sweden, UK, USA, France, etc.) counts place of birth and includes naturalised immigrants. "Foreign nationals" (Switzerland, Austria, Portugal, Spain, Italy, Czechia, etc.) counts current citizenship and excludes those who have naturalised. As a result, "foreign-born" figures are generally higher than "foreign national" figures for the same country.</li>
      <li><strong>Norway's narrow definition</strong>: Statistics Norway (SSB) defines "immigrants" (innvandrere) as persons where both parents were born abroad and who were themselves born abroad. This is narrower than most "foreign-born" definitions used elsewhere, which may include persons with only one foreign-born parent.</li>
      <li><strong>Denmark's two-tier count</strong>: Statistics Denmark (DST) separately tracks "immigrants" (indvandrere, 12.6%) and "descendants" (efterkommere, 3.7%). The combined figure is 16.3%. This chart uses the immigrants-only figure for consistency with other countries' first-generation measures.</li>
      <li><strong>Germany's migration background</strong>: Destatis/Mikrozensus reports 25.6% of the population had a "migration background" (Migrationshintergrund) in 2024 — meaning the person themselves, or at least one parent, was an immigrant or foreign-born. This broader definition is not comparable to the foreign-national or foreign-born measures used by other countries in this comparison.</li>
      <li><strong>Netherlands — methodology change</strong>: CBS (Statistics Netherlands) discontinued the "migration background" (migratieachtergrond) classification in 2024. A comparable, up-to-date foreign-born or foreign-national share could not be confirmed from primary sources for this edition.</li>
      <li><strong>Belgium's layered count</strong>: Statbel counts three groups: Belgians of Belgian origin (63.4%), Belgians of foreign origin (22.8%), and non-Belgian nationals (13.8%). This page uses the 13.8% non-Belgian nationals figure. The combined "foreign-origin" population (Belgians of foreign origin + non-Belgians) reaches 36.6%.</li>
      <li><strong>Canada — data lag</strong>: The 23.0% figure reflects the 2021 Census. Since then, Canada experienced record population growth (3.2% in 2023), with 97.6% of that growth attributable to international migration. The current share is likely higher but has not yet been confirmed by a new census.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="table-section">
    <h2>Country-by-Country Data</h2>
    <div class="table-wrapper">
      <table class="comparison-table">
        <thead>
